body:
A piece of laboratory equipment that produces a single open gas flame, which is used for heating, sterilization, and combustion.

The standard device, such as those used in a laboratory, use an external source of fuel, commonly methane, which is connected to the burner by a rubber hose.  There are portable types that use small canisters of gas, commonly butane, directly connected to the device.

The plot centers around [[Luka_(mon-musu_quest!)|]], a young boy who initially sets out to defeat the Monster Lord [[Alipheese Fateburn XVI|Alice]]. title: devastator_(transformers)
body:
A character from the [[Transformers]] science fiction franchise.

[b]Devastator[/b] is an evil [i][[Constructicon]][/i] [[Decepticon]], a powerful, big and sentient green, grey, purple and black [[alien]] [[robot]] that results from the combination of six different construction-themed smaller robots.

Devastator is notable because he was the very first [i]combiner[/i] among the original Transformers. In [[Japan]] his name was changed to [b]Devastar[/b] (デバスター).

Motto: [i]"Thinking and winning do not mix!...".[/i]

body:
An American thriller film directed and co-written by Roland Emmerich, is the first [[Godzilla (series)|]] film to be completely produced by a Hollywood studio. The film stars Matthew Broderick, [[Jean Reno]], Maria Pitillo, Hank Azaria, Kevin Dunn, Michael Lerner, and Harry Shearer.

In the film, authorities investigate and battle a [[Zilla|giant monster]] who migrates to [[New York City]] to nest its young.

The film was heavily panned by both critics and Godzilla fans, primarily due to its unfaithful characterization of [[Godzilla]].

title: norman_osborn
body: Norman Virgil Osborn is a character appearing in American comic books published by [[Marvel]] Comics. Created by writer [[Stan Lee]] and artist Steve Ditko, he debuted in [[Spider-man (series)|The Amazing Spider-Man #14]] (July 1964) as the first and best-known incarnation of the [[Green Goblin]]. He has since endured as one of the superhero [[spider-man|Spider-Man's]] most prominent villains and is regarded as one of his three archenemies, alongside [[Doctor Octopus]] and [[Venom (marvel)|]].
other_names: ノーマン・オズボーン

title: otto_octavius
body:
A ficticional character from the [[Marvel]] universe, also known as [[Doctor Octopus]].
The character was created by [[Stan Lee]] and Steve Ditko and first appeared in [[Spider-man (series)|The Amazing Spider-Man #3]] (July 1963). He is a highly intelligent, myopic, and stocky [[mad scientist]] who sports four strong and durable appendages resembling an octopus's tentacles, which extend from his body and can be used for various purposes. After his mechanical harness became permanently fused to his body during a lab accident, he turned to a life of crime, and came into conflict with the superhero [[Spider-Man]]. He has endured as one of Spider-Man's most prominent villains, and is regarded as one of his three archenemies, alongside the [[Green Goblin]] and [[Venom (marvel)|]]. He is the founder and leader of the Sinister Six, the first supervillain team to oppose Spider-Man.

title: east_germany
body:
Pertaining to the former [b]German Democratic Republic[/b] (in German: [i]Deutsche Demokratische Republik[/i]).

After [[World War II]], [[Germany]] was split into four occupation zones for the victorious Allied powers: the United States, United Kingdom, France and the Soviet Union. Differences between the western nations and the Soviet Union led to the long-term division of Germany with the creation of the Federal Republic of Germany ([[West Germany]]) and the German Democratic Republic in 1949. 

A hardline satellite nation of the [[soviet|Soviet Union]], its communist controlled government ruled East Germany until anti-communism movements swept Eastern Europe in 1989 and the now-defunct DDR was reunited with the western half of Germany on 3 October 1990.

title: toy_packaging
body:
Packaging used to display a [[toy]] for sale in a [[shop]].

This is often of the form of a plastic clam-shell inside a [[cardboard box|cardboard]] [[box]] (common for e.g. [[figure]]s and [[doll]]s) with (or without) a window in the front, a plastic [[blister pack]] with a cardboard backing (common for e.g. smaller [[toy car]]s), or a thermally sealed [[plastic bag]].  In all cases, there will be the product name printed somewhere on the package, and possibly a UPC [[bar code]] or [[price tag]].

The contents may be an actual toy, a [[model kit]], an inanimate [[character doll]] or [[character charm|charm]], a miniaturized version of a living character ([[miniboy]] or [[minigirl]]), or possibly a scaled-up version of such a box with the actual living character inside.  In the latter two cases, the character might be described as [[encasement|encased]] or [[restrained]].

h4. Examples

* !post #5401837: A boxed clam-shell with a display widow
* !post #5216348: A printed cardboard box without a window
* !post #7618747: A blister pack with cardboard backing
* !post #6744990: A thermally sealed plastic bag

h4. See also

* [[box]] - any kind of cuboid container
** [[cardboard box]] - a box made of cardboard, usually unprinted, meant for e.g. shipping rather than sale as with this tag
** [[display case]] - a large box or cabinet for displaying something (usually glass)
** [[gift box]] - a nice box likely wrapped and perhaps with a bow or ribbon for presenting something as a gift
** [[toy box]] - a large chest or container for storing many toys (often in a child's bedroom or playroom)
* [[model kit]] - a set of plastic parts (usually combined on a [[sprue]]) to be assembled into a complete figure or model
* [[food packaging]]

title: food_packaging
body:
Packaging used to display [[food]] for sale in a [[shop]] (such as a [[supermarket]]).

This might be a disposable printed [[box]], [[squeeze bottle]], [[carton]], [[canister]], thermally sealed [[bag]], [[jar]], [[can]], [[styrofoam]] [[tray]] [[shrink wrap]]ped in [[plastic wrap]], etc. These should include the product's name and potentially a UPC [[bar code]] or [[price tag]].

Do not use this for things such as drink [[bottle]]s and [[can]]s or [[juice box]]es, or [[food wrapper]]s intended for individual serving (which are overly common and better served by their own tags). This also obviously doesn't apply for unpackaged food (such as loose produce, raw fish or meat on ice, unwrapped bread at a bakery, etc).

title: gashapon
body:
A [[vending machine]] that randomly dispenses encapsulated [[toy]]s or the rounded capsules themselves. 'Gashapon' is comprised of two Japanese onomatopoeia; 'gasha' for the sound of the crank on the vending machine, and 'pon' for the sound of the toy dropping into the receptacle. Also known as "gachapon" due to copyright reason, as the word "gashapon" was patented by [[Bandai]], the original creator of the machine.

A genre of mobile video games have emerged called [i][[gacha (game mechanic)|]] games[/i] ("gacha" being an alternate reading of "gasha") that use a similar randomized element. This tag refers to the physical machine, plastic capsule, and toy.

Kyoko is a gentle teen who makes a perfect housewife. Her notably nice attitude is often considered to be her most notable trait. Kyoko is sweet and gentle, with the perk of being good at housework. Her hair is usually tied with a ribbon into a [[side ponytail]].

It has been shown in her "The Seven Mysteries of Sacred Slipper Academy" S Rare+, that she can look more menacing than she usually does. Fans say that Kyoko has the possibility of crossing into yandere territory, however it is more likely that she is taking the role seriously.

In the tie in Cinderella Girls Theater skits, Kyoko is a sweet girl who has a joyful disposition. She loves to clean and enjoys remembering her journey as an idol. Kyoko admits that she likes the Producer enough to marry him, and hopes to share an umbrella with him when she’s caught in the rain. Her kindheartedness is displayed when she delivers Christmas presents with her fellow idols to [[Sajo Yukimi]] and how she takes care of the Producer on their day off at the beach. She seems to have trouble drawing cats, as they tend to look more like rabbits, and loves to cook.

Due to her popularity, she was selected for the 9th set of CINDERELLA MASTER CD series, alongside [[Ninomiya Asuka]], [[Ohtsuki Yui]], [[Nakano Yuka]], and [[Aiba Yumi]]. She is voiced by [[Tanezaki Atsumi]].

title: salamander_(game)
body:
[i][b]Salamander[/b][/i], retitled [i][b]Life Force[/b][/i] in North America and in the Japanese [[arcade]] re-release, is a [[science fiction]] 2D scrolling shooter arcade [[video game]] by [[Konami]]. 

Released in 1986 as a spin-off to [[Gradius]], Salamander introduced a simplified power-up system, two-player cooperative gameplay (using two [[starfighter]]s, the original [[Vic Viper]] and a new one called [[Lord British]]) and both horizontally and vertically scrolling stages. Some of these later became the norm for future Gradius games.

The game was ported to the [[Famicom]] and the [[NES]] a year later. It also has been released on the Amstrad CPC, Commodore 64 and ZX Spectrum, the NEC [[Pc Engine]], the [[Sony]] [[PlayStation 1]], the [[Sega Saturn]], on mobile phones, the [[PlayStation Portable]] and the [[PlayStation 4]] in the last years. 

Salamander was followed with an official sequel in 1996 entitled [[Salamander 2]].

title: gerwalk
body:
[b]GERWALK[/b] ([b]G[/b]round [b]E[/b]ffective [b]R[/b]einforcement of [b]W[/b]inged [b]A[/b]rmament with [b]L[/b]ocomotive [b]K[/b]nee-joint) is a [[VTOL]] transformation mode of the [[VF-1]] [[variable fighter]] from [[MACROSS]] (and other related transformable [[mecha]]) where the nose and wings of the fighter [[jet]] are stuck on "chicken [[walker (robot)|]]" legs with two arms. The legs are formed by the aircraft's engines and intakes, bent down and forward. The arms are stored between the engines in fighter mode and fold out to the sides, reaching around from behind the legs.

Legend tells that when [[Kawamori Shouji]] first designed the VF-1 [i]Valkyrie[/i], he did not include this mode initially at all. However, after receiving a prototype of a toy based in the VF-1 he noticed that the legs of the figure were very very loose and constantly fell down during transformation into jet mode, so it resembled a unused walker mecha design called "Gawalk" that he developed years before for another show. Thus he adopted the mode in the mecha and changed its name into "Gerwalk" afterwards. 

h4.Other mecha that feature this mode

* The [[orguss_(mecha)|Orguss]] from [[Choujikuu Seiki Orguss]].
* The [[Legioss]] from [[Kikou Souseiki Mospeada]].
* The [[TASC-01-SCF_Logan|Logan]] and the [[Spartas]] from [[Choujikuu Kidan Southern Cross]].
* [[Opa-Opa]] from the [[Fantasy Zone]] [[video game]] series. 
* The [[mr._heli_(mecha)|titular mecha helicopter]] from the [[Mr. HELI]] 1987 video game.

title: du_fu
body:
Du Fu (Pinyin: Dù Fǔ, Wade-Giles: Tu Fu; Japanese: To Ho; 712–770) 

A [[China|Chinese]] scholar-official and poet of the Tang Dynasty, whose minor career in civil service was cut permanently short due to the An Lushan Rebellion in 755, at which point he took up a reclusive lifestyle much like his elder contemporary, [[Li Bai]]. 

Unlike Li, his reputation at home and abroad took off only in the centuries following his death, but the two are now both considered to be the greatest poets of the Tang, and among the greatest in the Chinese literary canon. 

Would become the subject of the [[meme]] "[i][[Du fu hen mang]][/i]", as well as being [[du fu (sangai senki)|reimagined as a female character]] in the game [[Sangai Senki]].

title: azalea_(flower)
body:
Azalea flowers are small flowers with shades of pink and purple. They are part of the Ericaceae family of flowers, blooming from late spring to early summer.

Not to be confused with [[lily (flower)|lilies]]. The typical azalea flower has [i]five[/i] petals, while lilies have [i]six[/i].

* !post #4473726

title: anthurium
body:
These are flowers with an asymmetrical shape, slightly resembling that of an oblong [[lily pad]], with a small stalk growing off-center from the main part, which is essentially a single large petal. 

Their colors range from red to shades of pink, and less commonly green and orange.

title: photocopier
body:
A machine that makes copies of documents and images onto paper.   In the past such machines used to be specialized in making photocopies, but that role today has been subsumed by large office multi-function [[printer]]s that can make photocopies, print files, scan documents, and send faxes.

The American company Xerox was a dominant maker of photocopiers to the extent that their name became a genericized byword to mean photocopier and the act of making a photocopy.

h4. External links

title: fumetsu_no_anata_e
body:
Fumetsu no Anata e is a Japanese manga series written and illustrated by [[ooima_yoshitoki|Ōima Yoshitoki]]. 

It has been serialized in Weekly Shōnen Magazine since November 2016, with the individual chapters collected and published by Kodansha into fourteen tankōbon volumes as of December 2020. 

The story follows an immortal being whose purpose is to gain knowledge of the world. As the story progresses, this being takes the form of an abandoned boy and his wolf.

An anime television series adaptation by Brain's Base premiered on April 12, 2021, after a 6 month delay due to COVID-19, and a sequel is due for release on Fall 2022.

title: tumblr_sexyman_tournament
body:
A Twitter tournament based around the [[meme]] discussing the trend of unconventional-looking characters being considered attractive and popular that started on [[Tumblr]], often to the bewilderment of other websites, said sites having joined in since.

The tournament itself was held on September 6th, 2022, ending with the final match between [[Sans (undertale)|]] from [i][[Undertale]][/i] and [[Reigen Arataka]] from [i][[Mob Psycho 100]][/i]. Reigen had, leading up to the tournament, won two other tournaments declaring him both "Twink Supreme":https://twitter.com/lgbtbeam/status/1565399868402696192 and the "Ultimate DILF":[https://twitter.com/denjictrl/status/1567125015656628225], so voting for this finale was intense. Sans would ultimately beat Reigen out by 0.1%, to mass celebration. Several memes would spawn out of this, from [[Elizabeth II]] passing away in the meantime being attributed to the intensity of the finale, to Toby Fox himself "writing":https://twitter.com/tobyfox/status/1567739718762364929 a scene depicting the ending. Reigen would then go on to win the "Superior MILF":[https://twitter.com/scrtvplotter/status/1567954322566295553], the "Hottest Anime Woman":[https://twitter.com/genicecream/status/1568754222312861696], and the "True Babygirl":[https://twitter.com/ranpoedgw/status/1568792119141347328] in three other tournaments. This would then ultimately be capped off with the official Undertale x Requiem Café event in Anaheim, California serving the unofficial "Reigen Supreme" "drink":https://twitter.com/kellyonelani/status/1575712882423083008 for $4.20 after running out of "Sans Soda".

The tournament was later rerun on Tumblr, and won by Cecil Palmer from [[Welcome to Night Vale]].

title: holy_roman_empire
body:
[b]The Holy Roman Empire[/b], also known as [b]The First Reich[/b] or [b]The Holy Roman Empire of the [[germany|German]] Nation[/b] after 1512, was a polity in Central and Western Europe, usually headed by the Holy Roman emperor. It developed in the [[medieval|Early Middle Ages]] and lasted for almost one thousand years until its dissolution in 1806 during the Napoleonic Wars.

On 25 December 800, Pope Leo III crowned Frankish king [[Charlemagne]] as Roman emperor, reviving the title in Western Europe more than three centuries after the fall of the ancient Western [[Roman Empire]] in 476. The title lapsed in 924, but was revived in 962 when [[Otto I]] was crowned emperor by Pope John XII, fashioning himself as Charlemagne's and the Carolingian Empire's successor, and beginning a continuous existence of the empire for over eight centuries.

From 962 until the twelfth century, the empire was the most powerful monarchy in Europe. The functioning of government depended on the harmonious cooperation between emperor and vassals; this harmony was disturbed during the Salian period. The empire reached the apex of territorial expansion and power under the House of Hohenstaufen in the mid-thirteenth century, but overextension led to a partial collapse.

While the office of emperor had been reestablished, the exact term for his realm as the "Holy Roman Empire" was not used until the 13th century. A process of Imperial Reform in the late fifteenth and early sixteenth centuries transformed the empire, creating a set of institutions which endured until its final demise in the nineteenth century. On 6 August 1806, Emperor Francis II dissolved the empire following the creation – the month before, by [[france|French]] emperor [[Napoleon Bonaparte]] – of the Confederation of the Rhine, a confederation of German client states loyal not to the Holy Roman emperor but to France.

title: aren't_grim_reapers_supposed_to_be_scary
body:
Visual novel created by the artist and animator [[Kamuo]].

The plot focuses on a young man, who apparently died in unknown circumstances, having zero memories or recollections of the past. Accepting his fate, and ready for the eternal rest, he slowly wakes up in a mysterious reality, surrounded of cute girls claiming to be grim reapers. Naturally confused, but having no reasons to doubt them, the protagonist wants answers, nevertheless, the grim reapers are as confused as him about why he came to their dimension, or who is him in the first place. The only option left to get the answers he wants, is accept the help of the grim reapers and their conditions to understand who, or what he is.

The last official update of the game was released during April, 2022. Since then, no official updates for the game has been released, and the creator declared he is not satisfied with his own visual novel. And while he was willing to continue the project, he was simply not happy with the art and the direction of the game mechanics, so he was re-working on the game from zero, hoping to get better results. Currently, the game is still on hiatus, and its future is still unknown.

title: kazama_jin
body:
Kazama Jin is one of the main characters of the [[Tekken]] series.

First appearing in [[Tekken 3]], Jin is the son of [[Kazama Jun]] and [[Mishima Kazuya]]. He was raised by his mother; Jun, for most of his young life until he turned 15, when his mother was supposedly murdered by [[Ogre (Tekken)|]], an ancient being known as "Toshin, the God of Fighting." He was taken in by his grandfather, [[Mishima Heihachi]] who taught him Mishima Style Karate. Jin was able to defeat Ogre, winning the King of Iron Fist Tournament 3 but was betrayed and almost shot dead by Heihachi.

From [[Tekken 4]] onward, he would use traditional Karate instead of Mishima style to fall more in line with his mother's teachings and to distance himself from his Mishima heritage. In [[Tekken 5]], his [[dark persona]], [[Devil Jin]] became a playable character, using his moveset from games prior to Tekken 4. 

In [[Tekken 6]], after defeating [[Mishima Jinpachi]] in the previous tournament. Jin was declared the new head of the Mishima Zaibatsu. He used his new leadership to wage a world war, and to host the King of Iron Fist Tournament 6. However, he was bested by [[Lars Alexandersson]].

Jin is characterized by his altruism, as evident by his interactions with [[Ling Xiaoyu]] and [[Hwoarang (Tekken)|]]. He plans to end the Mishima bloodline by killing Heihachi, Kazuya and then himself. 

Jin's outfits usually consist of black pants or hooded jackets with a flame motif. In Tekken 3 and [[Tekken Tag Tournament]], he had a school uniform alternate costume alongside Xiaoyu, as they both attended the same high school. In Tekken 6, he wears a business suit alternate costume and an emperor outfit designed by [[CLAMP (circle)|]]. His [[Tekken 7]] outfit was designed by [[Kozaki Yuusuke]].

title: about:note_fonts
body: The font of a translation note can be altered from the site default by using the CSS property [code]font-family[/code]. h4. Usage Add the property name and desired font name to the [b]style[/b] attribute of the surrounding HTML block. * Example: [code]This text will use a serif font[/code] h4. Name specification Single word fonts can be used as is. Multiple word fonts usually must be surrounded by apostrophes. * Example: [code]This text will use the Times New Roman font[/code] h4. Generic fonts There are five generic fonts which are available on all systems. The browser will pick the first available preferred font available on the user's OS. The generic font names are: * serif * sans-serif * monospace * cursive * fantasy h4. Multiple fonts The [code]font-family[/code] property allows multiple fonts to be listed as fallback fonts. Each font name needs to be separated by a comma. The browser will use the first available font from among those listed. * Example: [code]This text will use a font[/code] In the above example, if Times New Roman is on the system, the browser will use that font. Otherwise it will pick its preferred serif font. [tn][b]Note:[/b] It is generally suggested to always end a font list with a generic font. Otherwise, the font used will be dependent upon the browser.[/tn] h4. Danbooru-supplied fonts Danbooru supplies a set list of fonts available to use which acts as a guarantee that that font will be available to use on every browser and OS. * [b]comic[/b] - "Comic Relief":[https://fontlibrary.org/en/font/comic-relief], a Comic Sans replacement. * [b]narrow[/b] - "Archivo Narrow":[https://fonts.google.com/specimen/Archivo+Narrow], an Arial Narrow replacement. Narrow and thin. * [b]mono[/b] - "IBM's Plex Mono":[https://fonts.google.com/specimen/IBM+Plex+Mono], a monospace font for use on code or robot-like text. * [b]slab sans[/b] - "Anton":[https://fonts.google.com/specimen/Anton], an Impact replacement. Narrow and thick. * [b]slab serif[/b] - "Rokkitt":[https://fonts.google.com/specimen/Rokkitt], a Rockwell replacement. A blocky serif font. Sometimes used for comic titles. * [b]formal serif[/b] - "Lora":[https://fonts.google.com/specimen/Lora], a rounded, more formal serif font. * [b]formal cursive[/b] - "Petit Formal Script":[https://fonts.google.com/specimen/Petit+Formal+Script], a fancy cursive font. * [b]print[/b] - "Kalam":[https://fonts.google.com/specimen/Kalam], a neatly hand-printed font. Comparable to MV Boli. Suitable for neat handwriting or comics. * [b]hand[/b] - "Indie Flower":[https://fonts.google.com/specimen/Indie+Flower], a more casual handwritten font. Comparable to Segoe Print. * [b]childlike[/b] - "Giselle Script":[https://www.1001freefonts.com/gisele-script.font], a more-heavily stylized handwritten font. It has a lot of nice simple loops typical of what one might find in a children's course on teaching the alphabet. * [b]blackletter[/b] - "Unifraktur Maguntia":[https://fonts.google.com/specimen/UnifrakturMaguntia], a Gothic / Germanic / Old English style font. * [b]scary[/b] - "Anarchy":[https://www.dafont.com/anarchy-2.font], with jagged wild strokes. [tn][b]Note:[/b]The multiple word fonts that Danbooru provides do not need to be surrounded by apostrophes. Only the bolded font aliases will work, not the actual font names. For example, use [code]hand[/code], not [code]'Indie Flower'[/code].[/tn] Additionally, the following standard fonts have been aliased to other fonts: * [b]Comic Sans MS[/b] is now aliased to [b]Comic Relief[/b]. * [b]Arial Narrow[/b] is now aliased to [b]Archivo Narrow[/b]. * [b]Rockwell[/b] is now aliased to [b]Rokkitt[/b]. * [b]Impact[/b] is now aliased to [b]Anton[/b]. [tn]Using specific fonts besides the Danbooru-supplied and generic font families is discouraged and support for them will be removed in the future.[/tn] h5. title: pull_cord
body:
A pull cord is a mechanism that operates a device by means of pulling a cord. Common examples include:

* Cords connected to the built in switch of an electric [[lamp]] particularly common on certain types of [[ceiling light]]s.
* Cords that would wind up the voice mechanism of older mechanical talking [[doll]]s and [[toy]]s. These often have a ring-shaped handle. 
* Cords used for starting small engines without a starter motor (e.g. on a [[lawnmower|push-mower]] or [[chainsaw]]). These often have a T-shaped handle.

title: ootachi
body:
A type of Japanese [[sword]]. The ootachi (also known as 野太刀, [i]"nodachi"[/i]) is essentially a [[katana]] with a very long blade, often longer than the wielder's height. The best-known examples are probably [[Sephiroth]]'s Masamune in [i][[Final Fantasy VII]][/i] and the various long sword-class weapons featured in the [i][[Monster Hunter (series)|]][/i] series.

The ootachi was a rare weapon. In real life, it was used by men on foot to fight against mounted cavalry, however [[polearm]]s were much easier to produce and in most cases were more effective in that role. Due to it being an expensive weapon that was difficult to forge, it was seen as proof of a swordsmith's skill and a status symbol for a samurai who carried it.

title: honey_the_cat
body:
A [[sonic_(series)|Sonic]] character based off of [[honey_(fighting_vipers)|Honey]] from [i][[Fighting Vipers]][/i], a fighting game series also by Sega. 

She was originally meant to appear in [i]Sonic the Fighters[/i] and even had a complete model and moveset, but was ultimately scrapped from the arcade game for unknown reasons. However, her data was still present within the game, ergo making it possible to still play as her via hacking. Honey was eventually restored into [i]Sonic the Fighters[/i] officially when it was remastered for its digital release on Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 in 2012. Just highlight Amy, press the start button, and then select! 

Honey would make further appearances as a prominent character in the Sonic comics published by Archie Comics and made a cameo in the Sonic the Hedgehog Free Comic Book Day 2021 issue by IDW Publishing.
